ANTHRAX - ZAMBIA (08): (MUCHINGA) HIPPOPOTAMUS, OIE
***************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 31 Oct 2016
Source: OIE, WAHID (World Animal Health Information Database), weekly disease information 2016; 29(44) [edited]
http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapFullEventReport&reportid=21392


Anthrax, Zambia
---------------
Information received on [and dated] on 31 Oct 2016 from Dr Yona Sinkala, Director, Department of Veterinary Services, Ministry of Agriculture and Livestock, Lusaka, Zambia

Summary
Report type: Immediate notification
Date of start of the event: 20 Sep 2016
Date of confirmation of the event: 12 Oct 2016
Date submitted to OIE: 31 Oct 2016
Reason for notification: Reoccurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: September 2011
Manifestation of disease: Clinical disease
Causal agent: _Bacillus anthracis_
Nature of diagnosis: Laboratory (advanced)
This event pertains to a defined zone within the country

New outbreaks (1)
Outbreak 1: North Luangwa Game Management Area, Chama, Eastern
Date of start of the outbreak: 20 Sep 2016
Outbreak status: Continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: Not applicable
Affected animals:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Hippopotamus: _Hippopotamus amphibious_ (Hippopotamidae) / 200 / 18 / 18/ 0 / 0
Affected population: The affected hippos live along the valley of the Luangwa River (in Chikwa area) in the Game Management Area (GMA) which surrounds the North Luangwa National Park.

Summary of outbreaks: Total outbreaks: 1
Total animals affected:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Hippopotamus: _Hippopotamus amphibious_ (Hippopotamidae) / 200 / 18 / 18/ 0 / 0
Outbreak statistics [rates apparent, expressed as percentages]:
Species / Morbidity rate / Mortality rate / Case fatality rate / Proportion susceptible animals lost*
Hippopotamus:_Hippopotamus amphibious_(Hippopotamidae) / 9 / 9 / 100 / 9
*Removed from the susceptible population through death, destruction and/or slaughter

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: Unknown or inconclusive
Epidemiological comments: Surveillance ongoing. No mortalities in hippos have been recorded since 30 Sep 2016. Cattle in surrounding areas have been vaccinated.

Control measures
Measures applied: Disinfection/disinfestation; surveillance outside containment and/or protection zone; surveillance within containment and/or protection zone; vaccination permitted (if a vaccine exists); no treatment of affected animals
Measures to be applied: No other measures

Diagnostic test results:
Laboratory name and type / Species / Test / Test date / Result
Central Veterinary Research Institute (national laboratory) / Hippopotamus / polymerase chain reaction (PCR) / 12 Oct 2016 / Positive

Future reporting
The event is continuing. Weekly follow-up reports will be submitted.

[The location of the outbreak can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[This is but the official report to OIE in Paris. Chama is in Muchinga Province, part of what was known as the Eastern Province. The dates differ slightly from what we reported earlier but the differences are trivial. - Mod.MHJ

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4602202,2306.]
